{"title_page": "Flag of Mississippi", "text_new": "{{use American English|date=January 2015}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox flag\n | Name       = Mississippi\n | Image      = Flag of Mississippi.svg\n | Alt        = Flag of Mississippi\n | Use        = 010000\n | Symbol     = [[File:IFIS Equal.svg]]\n | Proportion = 2:3\n | Adoption   = {{Start date and age|1894|02|07}}\n | Design     = Three equal horizontal [[triband (flag)|tribands]] of blue, white, and red. The canton is square, bearing a blue cross, consists of a red background with a blue [[saltire]], bordered with white, and emblazoned with thirteen (13) five-pointed stars.\n | Designer   = Edward N. Scudder\n}}\nThe '''flag of Mississippi''' is the [[state flag]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Mississippi]]. It consists of three equal horizontal [[triband (flag)|tribands]] of blue, white, and red, with a red square in the [[Glossary of vexillology#Description of standard flag parts and terms|canton]] (referred to specifically as the \"union\") bearing a blue saltire, bordered with white and emblazoned with thirteen small, white, [[five-pointed star]]s. The 13 stars on the flag correspond to the original number of the states of the Union.<ref name=\"MS GOV\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ms.gov/Visitors/About_Mississippi/State_Flags|title= State Flags|access-date=July 5, 2019}}</ref> The canton portion of the flag also corresponds to the design of the U.S. civil war era battle flag of the Army of Northern Virginia, which over time has come to represent the unrecognized would-be republic known as Confederate States of America. The current design was adopted in 1894.<ref name=\"MS GOV\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ms.gov/Visitors/About_Mississippi/State_Flags|title= State Flags|access-date=July 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe design of the State flag has been modified officially two times since 1861. The current version is the longest-used and has been in use for over {{age|1894|2|7}} years.<ref name=\"MDAH\">{{cite web|url=http://mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us/articles/105/flags-over-mississippi|title=Flags Over Mississippi|last=Sansing|first=David G. |date=August 2000|website=[[Mississippi Department of Archives and History]]|publisher=[[Mississippi Historical Society]]|access-date=May 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===First flag===\n[[File:The Bonnie Blue Flag - Project Gutenberg eText 21566.jpg|thumb|260px|upright|left|[[The Bonnie Blue Flag]] by [[Harry McCarthy]]]]\n{{Infobox flag\n | Name = Mississippi\n | Image = Flag of Mississippi (1861\u20131865).gif\n | Alt = Flag of Mississippi\n | Nickname = Magnolia Flag\n | Use = 010000\n | Symbol = [[File:IFIS Equal.svg]]\n | Adoption = {{Start date|1861|03|30}}\n | Relinquished = {{End date|1865|08|22}}\n | Design = A white field with a large red border and [[magnolia]] tree in the center; in the canton, one white five-pointed star on a blue field.\n | Image2 = Flag of Mississippi (1861-1894).svg\n | Use2 = 010000\n | Symbol2 = [[File:IFIS Variant.svg]]\n | Design2 = Common unofficial flag variant (likely [[Post-war|postbellum]] and used by [[United Confederate Veterans|U.C.V.]] camps in Mississippi), similar to the \"Magnolia Flag.\"<ref name=\"Moss\">{{cite web |author1=Clay Moss |title=Mississippi's Magnolia Flags (U.S.) |url=https://fotw.info/flags/us-ms_mg.html |website=Flags of the World (FOTW) |publisher=Mississippi Department of Archives and History |accessdate=January 21, 2019 |date=June 21, 2015 |quote=It was likely a post-war flag, designed for use by one or more of Mississippi's United Confederate Veterans camps. Then over time, it was mistakenly identified as \"the\" Magnolia flag.}}</ref>\n | Designer   = Mississippi State Convention Committee to Prepare Flag and Coat of Arms for the State\n}}\nWhen the State of Mississippi declared its [[Secession in the United States|secession]] from the [[United States]] (\"[[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\") on January 9, 1861, near the start of the [[American Civil War]], spectators in the balcony handed a [[Bonnie Blue Flag]] down to the Mississippi state convention delegates on the convention floor,<ref name=\"mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us\">http://mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us/articles/105/flags-over-mississippi Flags Over Mississippi</ref> and one was raised over the [[Old Mississippi State Capitol|state capitol building]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi|Jackson]] as a sign of independence.<ref>Jau Winik, \"A New Flag for a New Mississippi,\" ''New York Times'', Feb. 11, 2001, Week in Review section, p. 17.</ref> Later that night residents of Jackson paraded through the streets under the banner. [[Harry McCarthy]], an Irish singer and playwright who observed the street parade, was inspired to write the patriotic song \"[[The Bonnie Blue Flag]],\" which, after \"[[Dixie (song)|Dixie]],\" was the most popular song in the [[Confederate States of America|Confederate States]] at the time.<ref name=\"MDAH\" /><ref>[http://www.washingtonartillery.com/Def.htm The Lone Star/Bonnie Blue Flag], Washington Artillery</ref>\n\nThe first flag of Mississippi was known as the \"Magnolia Flag.\" It was the official state flag from March 30, 1861, until August 22, 1865.<ref name=\"Moss\"/> The flag remained in use in an unofficial capacity until 1894,{{efn|The flag was first adopted in February 1894. However, it was repealed in 1906, remaining in ''de facto'' usage until its official re-adoption in April 2001.}} when the current version was first adopted.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.netstate.com/states/symb/flags/ms_flag.htm |title=Mississippi State Flag - About the Mississippi Flag, its adoption and history from NETSTATE.COM|website=www.netstate.com}}</ref> On January 26, 1861, the delegates to the state convention approved the report of a special committee that had been appointed to design a coat of arms and \"a suitable flag\".<ref name=\"mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us\"/> The flag recommended by the committee was \"A Flag of white ground, a [[magnolia]] tree in the centre<!-- please do not change to \"center;\" it's a quote -->, a blue field in the [[Canton (flag)#Description of standard flag parts and terms|upper left hand corner]] with a white star in the centre<!-- please do not change to \"center;\" it's a quote -->, the Flag to be finished with a red border and a red fringe at the extremity of the Flag.\"<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Journal of the State Convention, and Ordinances and Resolutions Adopted in January, 1861. with an Appendix |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofstateco00miss |others=Published by Order of the Convention |location=Jackson, Miss. |publisher=[[Ethelbert Barksdale|E. Barksdale]], State Printer |pages=[https://archive.org/details/journalofstateco00miss/page/89 89]\u201390 |date=1861 |lccn=16025853 |oclc=1047488108 |ol=24350027M |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref> Due to time constraints and the pressure to raise \"means for the defense of the state,\" the delegates neglected to adopt the flag officially in January but did so when they reassembled in March 1861.<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Journal of the State Convention and Ordinances and Resolutions Adopted in March, 1861 |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofstatecomiss |others=Published by Order of the Convention |location=Jackson |publisher=[[Ethelbert Barksdale|E. Barksdale]], State Printer |pages=[https://archive.org/details/journalofstatecomiss/page/43 43], 47, 86 |date=1861 |oclc=758987648 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref> The Magnolia Flag was not widely used or displayed during the [[American Civil War]], as the various [[Flags of the Confederate States of America|Confederate flags]] were displayed more frequently.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.netstate.com/states/symb/flags/ms_flag.htm |title=Mississippi State Flag - About the Mississippi Flag, its adoption and history from NETSTATE.COM |website=www.netstate.com}}</ref> Following the conclusion of the war, a Mississippi state [[Constitutional convention (political meeting)|constitutional convention]] that met in Jackson nullified many of the ordinances and resolutions passed by the conventions of 1861. Among those nullified was the 1861 ordinance \"to provide a Coat of Arms and Flag for the State of Mississippi,\" leaving Mississippi without an official state flag.<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Journal of the Proceedings and Debates in the Constitutional Convention of the State of Mississippi, August 1865 |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofprocee00miss |location=Jackson, Miss. |publisher=[[Edward M. Yerger|E. M. Yerger]], State Printer |pages=[https://archive.org/details/journalofprocee00miss/page/34 34]-36, 174, 221-225, 247 |date=1865 |lccn=10012152 |oclc=48174008 |ol=7019017M |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref>\n\n===Flag Act of 1894===\nOn February 7, 1894, the [[Mississippi Legislature|Legislature]] replaced the American Civil War era Magnolia Flag.<ref name=\"MDAH\" /> The flag was repealed in 1906, but remained in ''[[de facto]]'' use. When a referendum failed for a new design in April 2001,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Firestone|first1=David|title=Mississippi Votes by Wide Margin to Keep State Flag That Includes Confederate Emblem|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/18/us/mississippi-votes-wide-margin-keep-state-flag-that-includes-confederate-emblem.html|website=New York Times|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> the Legislature voted to readopt the historic design that same month.<ref name=3-3-16>{{cite web|url=http://www.lexisnexis.com/hottopics/mscode/|title=Miss. Code Ann. \u00a7 3-3-16: Design of state flag|work=Mississippi Code of 1972|author=State of Mississippi|publisher=LexisNexis|date=February 7, 2001|quote=HISTORY: SOURCES: Laws, 2001, ch. 301, \u00a7 2, eff from and after February 7, 2001 (the date the United States Attorney General interposed no objection under Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act of 1965, to the addition of this section.)}}</ref> Since [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] adopted a [[Flag of Georgia (U.S. state)|new state flag]] in 2003, the Mississippi flag is the only [[Flags of the U.S. states|U.S. state flag]] to include the Confederate battle flag's [[saltire]]. In 2001 a survey conducted by the [[North American Vexillological Association]] (NAVA) placed Mississippi's flag 22nd in design quality of the 72 Canadian provincial, U.S. state, and U.S. territorial flags ranked.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nava.org/digital-library/design/surveys/2001-State-Provincial-Flag-Survey.pdf|title=2001 State/Provincial Flag Survey  - NAVA.org|work=nava.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 1906 Mississippi adopted a revised legal code that repealed all general laws that were not reenacted by the legislature or brought forward in the new code.<ref name=\"MississippiWhitfield1906\">{{cite book|author1=Mississippi|author2=Albert Hall Whitfield|author3=Thomas Clendenin Catchings|author4=W. H. Hardy|title=The Mississippi code of 1906 of the public statute laws of the state of Mississippi, prepared and annotated by A. H. Whitfield, T. C. Catchings and W. H. Hardy: Under the provisions of an act of the Legislature approved March 19, 1904, and reported to and revised|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7QFQAAAAYAAJ|year=1906|publisher=Brandon printing company|page=141}}</ref> Because of this oversight, likely inadvertent, the state of Mississippi did not have a state flag from 1906 to 2001. Nonetheless, the 1894 flag continued to be used as the ''de facto'' state flag until it was officially readopted by the Legislature on April 17, 2001.<ref name=3-3-16/>\n\nThe Mississippi Code of 1972, in Title 3, Chapter 3, describes the flag as follows:\n\n<blockquote>\u00a7 3-3-16. Design of state flag.<!-- This is a direct quote; please do not change the text -->\nThe official flag of the State of Mississippi shall have the following design: with width two-thirds (2/3) of its length; with the union (canton) to be square, in width two-thirds (2/3) of the width of the flag; the ground of the union to be red and a broad blue saltire thereon, bordered with white and emblazoned with thirteen (13) [[Star (heraldry)#Terminology|mullets]] or five-pointed stars, corresponding with the number of the [[Thirteen Colonies|original States of the Union]]; the field to be divided into three (3) bars of equal width, the upper one blue, the center one white, and the lower one, extending the whole length of the flag, red ([[National colours|the national colors]]); this being the flag adopted by the Mississippi Legislature in the 1894 Special Session.<ref name=3-3-16/><ref name=Netstate>{{cite web|url=http://www.netstate.com/states/symb/flags/ms_flag.htm|work=NetState|title=The Mississippi State Flag|date=February 6, 2014|accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 2000 the [[Supreme Court of Mississippi]] ruled that the state legislature in 1906 had repealed the adoption of the state flag in 1894.<ref>''Mississippi Division of the United [[Sons of Confederate Veterans]] v. Mississippi State Conference of [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People|NAACP]] Branches'', 774 So.2d 388 (Miss. 2000)</ref> What was considered to be the official state flag was only so through custom or tradition during the previous 94 years.<ref name=\"Dedman\">{{cite journal|last=Dedman IV|first=James M.|title=At Daggers Drawn: The Confederate Flag and the School Classroom - A Case Study of a Broken First Amendment Formula|journal=Baylor Law Review|volume=53|pages=877, 883|publisher=|location= |date=Fall 2001|url=|doi= |id= |accessdate= }}</ref> The flag was officially readopted on April 17, 2001.<ref name=3-3-16/>\n\n===2001 referendum===\n[[File:Mississippi 2001 flag proposal.svg|thumb|{{FIAV|proposal}} 2001 flag proposal]]\nIn January 2001 then-Governor [[Ronnie Musgrove]] appointed an independent commission which developed a new proposed design.<ref name=Netstate/><ref name=\"Dedman\"/> On April 17, 2001, a non-binding state referendum to change the flag was put before Mississippi voters. The proposal would have replaced the Confederate battle flag with a blue [[Canton (flag)|canton]] with 20 stars. The outer ring of 13 stars would represent the original [[Thirteen Colonies]], the ring of six stars would represent the six nations that have had sovereignty over Mississippi Territory (various [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] nations as a collective nation, [[French colonial empire|French Empire]], [[Spanish Empire]], [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]], the United States, and the Confederacy), and the inner and slightly larger star would represent Mississippi itself. The 20 stars would also represent Mississippi's status as the 20th member of the United States.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}} The referendum for a new Mississippi state flag was defeated in a vote of 64% (488,630 votes) to 36% (267,812), and the 1894 state flag was retained.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.state.ms.us/elections/FlagVote/CountyScans/CertStateResults.pdf |title=Election Results |accessdate=2007-10-21 |date=2001-04-27 |format=PDF |publisher=State of Mississippi |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071126205132/http://www.sos.state.ms.us/elections/FlagVote/CountyScans/CertStateResults.pdf |archivedate=November 26, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nI LIKE MOOSEN\n\n==Pledge of Allegiance==\nThe pledge to the state flag is:\n\n{{quote|I salute the flag of Mississippi and the [[U.S. state|sovereign state]] for which it stands with pride in her history and achievements and with confidence in her future under the guidance of [[Ceremonial deism|Almighty God]].|source=MS Code \u00a7 37-13-7 (2018)}}\n\nThe Mississippi Code provides: \"The pledge of allegiance to the Mississippi flag shall be taught in the public schools of this state, along with the pledge of allegiance to the United States flag.\"<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=https://law.justia.com/codes/mississippi/2018/title-37/chapter-13/in-general/section-37-13-7/|title=MS Code \u00a7 37-13-7 (2018)}}</ref>\n\n==See also==<!-- EDITORS NOTE: This section should primarily contain lists linked to the main article which are directly related to the flag. Thank you. -->\n{{Portal|Heraldry|Mississippi}}\n* [[List of flags by design]]\n* [[List of Mississippi state symbols]]\n* [[List of U.S. state, district, and territorial insignia]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Cannon |first=Devereaux D., Jr. |date=2005 |orig-year=1st pub. St. Lukes Press:1988 |chapter=Chapter 7: State Flags |title=The Flags of the Confederacy: An Illustrated History |others=Cover design by Larry Pardue |location=[[Gretna, Louisiana|Gretna]] |publisher=[[Pelican Publishing Company]] |pages=34\u201348 |isbn=978-1-565-54109-2 |oclc=970744690}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Flags of Mississippi}}\n<!--\n  ===============================================================================\n   WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS. Only a limited number of new links\n   should be added to this article. PLEASE DO NOT ADD external links to sites with\n   information already in the article or in its sources.\n\n   See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for further details\n  ===============================================================================\n-->\n* {{FOTW|id=us-ms|title=Mississippi (U.S.)}}\n* [https://law.justia.com/codes/mississippi/2013/title-3/chapter-3/section-3-3-16/ Text] of the Mississippi Flag Code (MS Code \u00a7 3-3-16)\n<!-- EDITORS NOTE: Please follow the [[WP:EL]] guideline where possible and consider discussing on the talk page. Thank you. -->\n\n{{US state flags}}\n{{Mississippi}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Flags of Mississippi| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:1894 establishments in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Flag controversies in the United States|Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Flags introduced in 1894|Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Symbols of Mississippi|Flag]]\n[[Category:United States state flags|Mississippi]]\n", "text_old": "{{use American English|date=January 2015}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox flag\n | Name       = Mississippi\n | Image      = Flag of Mississippi.svg\n | Alt        = Flag of Mississippi\n | Use        = 010000\n | Symbol     = [[File:IFIS Equal.svg]]\n | Proportion = 2:3\n | Adoption   = {{Start date and age|1894|02|07}}\n | Design     = Three equal horizontal [[triband (flag)|tribands]] of blue, white, and red. The canton is square, bearing a blue cross, consists of a red background with a blue [[saltire]], bordered with white, and emblazoned with thirteen (13) five-pointed stars.\n | Designer   = Edward N. Scudder\n}}\nThe '''flag of Mississippi''' is the [[state flag]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Mississippi]]. It consists of three equal horizontal [[triband (flag)|tribands]] of blue, white, and red, with a red square in the [[Glossary of vexillology#Description of standard flag parts and terms|canton]] (referred to specifically as the \"union\") bearing a blue saltire, bordered with white and emblazoned with thirteen small, white, [[five-pointed star]]s. The 13 stars on the flag correspond to the original number of the states of the Union.<ref name=\"MS GOV\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ms.gov/Visitors/About_Mississippi/State_Flags|title= State Flags|access-date=July 5, 2019}}</ref> The canton portion of the flag also corresponds to the design of the U.S. civil war era battle flag of the Army of Northern Virginia, which over time has come to represent the unrecognized would-be republic known as Confederate States of America. The current design was adopted in 1894.<ref name=\"MS GOV\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ms.gov/Visitors/About_Mississippi/State_Flags|title= State Flags|access-date=July 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe design of the State flag has been modified officially two times since 1861. The current version is the longest-used and has been in use for over {{age|1894|2|7}} years.<ref name=\"MDAH\">{{cite web|url=http://mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us/articles/105/flags-over-mississippi|title=Flags Over Mississippi|last=Sansing|first=David G. |date=August 2000|website=[[Mississippi Department of Archives and History]]|publisher=[[Mississippi Historical Society]]|access-date=May 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===First flag===\n[[File:The Bonnie Blue Flag - Project Gutenberg eText 21566.jpg|thumb|260px|upright|left|[[The Bonnie Blue Flag]] by [[Harry McCarthy]]]]\n{{Infobox flag\n | Name = Mississippi\n | Image = Flag of Mississippi (1861\u20131865).gif\n | Alt = Flag of Mississippi\n | Nickname = Magnolia Flag\n | Use = 010000\n | Symbol = [[File:IFIS Equal.svg]]\n | Adoption = {{Start date|1861|03|30}}\n | Relinquished = {{End date|1865|08|22}}\n | Design = A white field with a large red border and [[magnolia]] tree in the center; in the canton, one white five-pointed star on a blue field.\n | Image2 = Flag of Mississippi (1861-1894).svg\n | Use2 = 010000\n | Symbol2 = [[File:IFIS Variant.svg]]\n | Design2 = Common unofficial flag variant (likely [[Post-war|postbellum]] and used by [[United Confederate Veterans|U.C.V.]] camps in Mississippi), similar to the \"Magnolia Flag.\"<ref name=\"Moss\">{{cite web |author1=Clay Moss |title=Mississippi's Magnolia Flags (U.S.) |url=https://fotw.info/flags/us-ms_mg.html |website=Flags of the World (FOTW) |publisher=Mississippi Department of Archives and History |accessdate=January 21, 2019 |date=June 21, 2015 |quote=It was likely a post-war flag, designed for use by one or more of Mississippi's United Confederate Veterans camps. Then over time, it was mistakenly identified as \"the\" Magnolia flag.}}</ref>\n | Designer   = Mississippi State Convention Committee to Prepare Flag and Coat of Arms for the State\n}}\nWhen the State of Mississippi declared its [[Secession in the United States|secession]] from the [[United States]] (\"[[Union (American Civil War)|Union]]\") on January 9, 1861, near the start of the [[American Civil War]], spectators in the balcony handed a [[Bonnie Blue Flag]] down to the Mississippi state convention delegates on the convention floor,<ref name=\"mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us\">http://mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us/articles/105/flags-over-mississippi Flags Over Mississippi</ref> and one was raised over the [[Old Mississippi State Capitol|state capitol building]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi|Jackson]] as a sign of independence.<ref>Jau Winik, \"A New Flag for a New Mississippi,\" ''New York Times'', Feb. 11, 2001, Week in Review section, p. 17.</ref> Later that night residents of Jackson paraded through the streets under the banner. [[Harry McCarthy]], an Irish singer and playwright who observed the street parade, was inspired to write the patriotic song \"[[The Bonnie Blue Flag]],\" which, after \"[[Dixie (song)|Dixie]],\" was the most popular song in the [[Confederate States of America|Confederate States]] at the time.<ref name=\"MDAH\" /><ref>[http://www.washingtonartillery.com/Def.htm The Lone Star/Bonnie Blue Flag], Washington Artillery</ref>\n\nThe first flag of Mississippi was known as the \"Magnolia Flag.\" It was the official state flag from March 30, 1861, until August 22, 1865.<ref name=\"Moss\"/> The flag remained in use in an unofficial capacity until 1894,{{efn|The flag was first adopted in February 1894. However, it was repealed in 1906, remaining in ''de facto'' usage until its official re-adoption in April 2001.}} when the current version was first adopted.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.netstate.com/states/symb/flags/ms_flag.htm |title=Mississippi State Flag - About the Mississippi Flag, its adoption and history from NETSTATE.COM|website=www.netstate.com}}</ref> On January 26, 1861, the delegates to the state convention approved the report of a special committee that had been appointed to design a coat of arms and \"a suitable flag\".<ref name=\"mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us\"/> The flag recommended by the committee was \"A Flag of white ground, a [[magnolia]] tree in the centre<!-- please do not change to \"center;\" it's a quote -->, a blue field in the [[Canton (flag)#Description of standard flag parts and terms|upper left hand corner]] with a white star in the centre<!-- please do not change to \"center;\" it's a quote -->, the Flag to be finished with a red border and a red fringe at the extremity of the Flag.\"<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Journal of the State Convention, and Ordinances and Resolutions Adopted in January, 1861. with an Appendix |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofstateco00miss |others=Published by Order of the Convention |location=Jackson, Miss. |publisher=[[Ethelbert Barksdale|E. Barksdale]], State Printer |pages=[https://archive.org/details/journalofstateco00miss/page/89 89]\u201390 |date=1861 |lccn=16025853 |oclc=1047488108 |ol=24350027M |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref> Due to time constraints and the pressure to raise \"means for the defense of the state,\" the delegates neglected to adopt the flag officially in January but did so when they reassembled in March 1861.<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Journal of the State Convention and Ordinances and Resolutions Adopted in March, 1861 |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofstatecomiss |others=Published by Order of the Convention |location=Jackson |publisher=[[Ethelbert Barksdale|E. Barksdale]], State Printer |pages=[https://archive.org/details/journalofstatecomiss/page/43 43], 47, 86 |date=1861 |oclc=758987648 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref> The Magnolia Flag was not widely used or displayed during the [[American Civil War]], as the various [[Flags of the Confederate States of America|Confederate flags]] were displayed more frequently.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.netstate.com/states/symb/flags/ms_flag.htm |title=Mississippi State Flag - About the Mississippi Flag, its adoption and history from NETSTATE.COM |website=www.netstate.com}}</ref> Following the conclusion of the war, a Mississippi state [[Constitutional convention (political meeting)|constitutional convention]] that met in Jackson nullified many of the ordinances and resolutions passed by the conventions of 1861. Among those nullified was the 1861 ordinance \"to provide a Coat of Arms and Flag for the State of Mississippi,\" leaving Mississippi without an official state flag.<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Journal of the Proceedings and Debates in the Constitutional Convention of the State of Mississippi, August 1865 |url=https://archive.org/details/journalofprocee00miss |location=Jackson, Miss. |publisher=[[Edward M. Yerger|E. M. Yerger]], State Printer |pages=[https://archive.org/details/journalofprocee00miss/page/34 34]-36, 174, 221-225, 247 |date=1865 |lccn=10012152 |oclc=48174008 |ol=7019017M |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref>\n\n===Flag Act of 1894===\nOn February 7, 1894, the [[Mississippi Legislature|Legislature]] replaced the American Civil War era Magnolia Flag.<ref name=\"MDAH\" /> The flag was repealed in 1906, but remained in ''[[de facto]]'' use. When a referendum failed for a new design in April 2001,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Firestone|first1=David|title=Mississippi Votes by Wide Margin to Keep State Flag That Includes Confederate Emblem|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/18/us/mississippi-votes-wide-margin-keep-state-flag-that-includes-confederate-emblem.html|website=New York Times|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> the Legislature voted to readopt the historic design that same month.<ref name=3-3-16>{{cite web|url=http://www.lexisnexis.com/hottopics/mscode/|title=Miss. Code Ann. \u00a7 3-3-16: Design of state flag|work=Mississippi Code of 1972|author=State of Mississippi|publisher=LexisNexis|date=February 7, 2001|quote=HISTORY: SOURCES: Laws, 2001, ch. 301, \u00a7 2, eff from and after February 7, 2001 (the date the United States Attorney General interposed no objection under Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act of 1965, to the addition of this section.)}}</ref> Since [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] adopted a [[Flag of Georgia (U.S. state)|new state flag]] in 2003, the Mississippi flag is the only [[Flags of the U.S. states|U.S. state flag]] to include the Confederate battle flag's [[saltire]]. In 2001 a survey conducted by the [[North American Vexillological Association]] (NAVA) placed Mississippi's flag 22nd in design quality of the 72 Canadian provincial, U.S. state, and U.S. territorial flags ranked.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nava.org/digital-library/design/surveys/2001-State-Provincial-Flag-Survey.pdf|title=2001 State/Provincial Flag Survey  - NAVA.org|work=nava.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 1906 Mississippi adopted a revised legal code that repealed all general laws that were not reenacted by the legislature or brought forward in the new code.<ref name=\"MississippiWhitfield1906\">{{cite book|author1=Mississippi|author2=Albert Hall Whitfield|author3=Thomas Clendenin Catchings|author4=W. H. Hardy|title=The Mississippi code of 1906 of the public statute laws of the state of Mississippi, prepared and annotated by A. H. Whitfield, T. C. Catchings and W. H. Hardy: Under the provisions of an act of the Legislature approved March 19, 1904, and reported to and revised|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7QFQAAAAYAAJ|year=1906|publisher=Brandon printing company|page=141}}</ref> Because of this oversight, likely inadvertent, the state of Mississippi did not have a state flag from 1906 to 2001. Nonetheless, the 1894 flag continued to be used as the ''de facto'' state flag until it was officially readopted by the Legislature on April 17, 2001.<ref name=3-3-16/>\n\nThe Mississippi Code of 1972, in Title 3, Chapter 3, describes the flag as follows:\n\n<blockquote>\u00a7 3-3-16. Design of state flag.<!-- This is a direct quote; please do not change the text -->\nThe official flag of the State of Mississippi shall have the following design: with width two-thirds (2/3) of its length; with the union (canton) to be square, in width two-thirds (2/3) of the width of the flag; the ground of the union to be red and a broad blue saltire thereon, bordered with white and emblazoned with thirteen (13) [[Star (heraldry)#Terminology|mullets]] or five-pointed stars, corresponding with the number of the [[Thirteen Colonies|original States of the Union]]; the field to be divided into three (3) bars of equal width, the upper one blue, the center one white, and the lower one, extending the whole length of the flag, red ([[National colours|the national colors]]); this being the flag adopted by the Mississippi Legislature in the 1894 Special Session.<ref name=3-3-16/><ref name=Netstate>{{cite web|url=http://www.netstate.com/states/symb/flags/ms_flag.htm|work=NetState|title=The Mississippi State Flag|date=February 6, 2014|accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 2000 the [[Supreme Court of Mississippi]] ruled that the state legislature in 1906 had repealed the adoption of the state flag in 1894.<ref>''Mississippi Division of the United [[Sons of Confederate Veterans]] v. Mississippi State Conference of [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People|NAACP]] Branches'', 774 So.2d 388 (Miss. 2000)</ref> What was considered to be the official state flag was only so through custom or tradition during the previous 94 years.<ref name=\"Dedman\">{{cite journal|last=Dedman IV|first=James M.|title=At Daggers Drawn: The Confederate Flag and the School Classroom - A Case Study of a Broken First Amendment Formula|journal=Baylor Law Review|volume=53|pages=877, 883|publisher=|location= |date=Fall 2001|url=|doi= |id= |accessdate= }}</ref> The flag was officially readopted on April 17, 2001.<ref name=3-3-16/>\n\n===2001 referendum===\n[[File:Mississippi 2001 flag proposal.svg|thumb|{{FIAV|proposal}} 2001 flag proposal]]\nIn January 2001 then-Governor [[Ronnie Musgrove]] appointed an independent commission which developed a new proposed design.<ref name=Netstate/><ref name=\"Dedman\"/> On April 17, 2001, a non-binding state referendum to change the flag was put before Mississippi voters. The proposal would have replaced the Confederate battle flag with a blue [[Canton (flag)|canton]] with 20 stars. The outer ring of 13 stars would represent the original [[Thirteen Colonies]], the ring of six stars would represent the six nations that have had sovereignty over Mississippi Territory (various [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] nations as a collective nation, [[French colonial empire|French Empire]], [[Spanish Empire]], [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]], the United States, and the Confederacy), and the inner and slightly larger star would represent Mississippi itself. The 20 stars would also represent Mississippi's status as the 20th member of the United States.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}} The referendum for a new Mississippi state flag was defeated in a vote of 64% (488,630 votes) to 36% (267,812), and the 1894 state flag was retained.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.state.ms.us/elections/FlagVote/CountyScans/CertStateResults.pdf |title=Election Results |accessdate=2007-10-21 |date=2001-04-27 |format=PDF |publisher=State of Mississippi |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071126205132/http://www.sos.state.ms.us/elections/FlagVote/CountyScans/CertStateResults.pdf |archivedate=November 26, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n==Future of the flag==\n[[File:Stennis-flag-Mississippi-proposal.svg|thumb|{{FIAV|proposal}} Stennis flag proposal (2014)]]\nIn the wake of the 2015 [[Charleston church shooting|Charleston, South Carolina church shooting]], in which nine Black parishioners of an [[Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church]] were killed by white supremacist [[Dylann Roof]], there were [[Modern display of the Confederate flag#Reactions to 2015 Charleston church shooting|renewed calls]] for Southern states to cease using the Confederate battle flag in official capacities.<ref name=\"cnn ms flag\">\"[http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/19/us/mississippi-state-flag/ Battle over Confederate symbols continues with Mississippi state flag].\" CNN. 2016-06-19. Retrieved 2017-05-06.</ref> This extended to increased criticism of Mississippi's state flag. All eight public universities in Mississippi, along with \"several cities and counties\", including [[Biloxi]], are now refusing to fly the state flag until the emblem is removed. At displays of all 50 state flags in [[New Jersey]], [[Oregon]], and [[Philadelphia]], the flag has been removed, leaving 49.<ref name=\"cnn ms flag\"/><ref>\"[http://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/politics/2017/04/24/biloxi-wont-fly-mississippi-state-flag/100862858/ Biloxi won't fly state flag].\" Associated Press (via ''Clarion-Ledger''). 2017-04-27. Retrieved 2017-05-06.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.reflector-online.com/news/article_62535ff6-6e52-11e6-b8a2-67837aa21aea.html|title=State flag quietly removed from campus|work=The Reflector|access-date=2017-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=University of Mississippi Lowers State Flag With Confederate Symbol|first=Daniel|last=Victor|date=October 26, 2015|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/27/us/university-mississippi-lowers-state-flag-confederate-emblem.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=New Jersey Governor Refuses to Fly 'Reprehensible' Mississippi Flag|first=James|last=Barron|date=April 29, 2019|newspaper=[[New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/29/nyregion/nj-mississippi-flag.html}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Flagpoles and building, Mississippi Welcome Center (Tremont).JPG|left|thumb|The Mississippi flag outside of a Mississippi Welcome Center in 2016.]]\nOver 20 flag-related bills, some calling for another statewide referendum, were introduced in the Legislature in 2015 and 2016, but none made it out of committee.<ref name=\"cnn ms flag\" /> A 2016 federal lawsuit alleging that the flag is tantamount to \"state-sanctioned hate speech\" was dismissed by both a district court and the [[5th Circuit Court of Appeals]].<ref>\"[https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/mississippi/articles/2017-03-06/confederate-themed-mississippi-flag-heading-back-to-court Mississippi Confederate Flag Fight Moves to New Battlefield].\" ''US News & World Report''. 2017-03-16. Retrieved 2017-05-06.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/04/03/522478779/court-rejects-lawsuit-against-mississippi-state-flags-confederate-symbolism Court Rejects Lawsuit Against Mississippi State Flag's Confederate Symbolism].\" 2017-04-03. Retrieved 2017-05-06.</ref> The [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] declined to hear the case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/search.aspx?filename=/docket/docketfiles/html/public/17-23.html|title=Search - Supreme Court of the United States|website=www.supremecourt.gov|access-date=2018-01-16}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Mississippi Stennis Car Tag.jpg|thumb|Mississippi specialty license plate advertising the Stennis flag proposal, made available for purchase in 2019.]]\nAn alternative was devised in 2014 by local artist Laurin Stennis, granddaughter of former U.S. senator [[John C. Stennis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/2016/02/20/watkins-stennis-granddaughter-offers-new-flag-option/80530800/|title=Watkins: Stennis granddaughter offers new flag option|website=The Clarion Ledger|language=en|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref> Her proposal was originally dubbed the \u201cDeclare Mississippi\u201d flag and has been popularly called the \"Stennis Flag\". As she explained it, the flag consists of a single blue star on a white field, an \"inverted\" Bonnie Blue Flag (white star on blue). It is encircled by 19 smaller stars, one for each state in the Union when Mississippi joined it, and is flanked on each side by a vertical red band, representing \"blood spilled by Mississippians\".<ref name=DeclareMississippi>{{Cite web|url=https://declaremississippi.com/stennisflagabout/|title=Stennis Flag|website=Stennis Flag|language=en|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref> Laurin Stennis' stated mission was to create \"an image that would better capture our history and hopes without denying or romanticizing our past\" and focus on HISTORY + HOPE + HOSPITALITY.<ref name=DeclareMississippi/>\n\nSince its inception, numerous bills have been brought before the Legislature to instate the Stennis Flag, but so far none have passed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://declaremississippi.com/stennisflagpress/|title=News|website=Stennis Flag|language=en|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.magnoliastatelive.com/2018/01/15/mississippis-state-flag-enough-support/|title=This should be Mississippi's state flag. And with enough support, it could be.|last=Monday|first=Joe Rogers Email the author Published 7:00 am|last2=January 15|date=2018-01-15|website=Magnolia State Live|access-date=2019-01-21|last3=2018}}</ref> On April 17, 2019, Mississippi governor [[Phil Bryant]] signed a new specialty license plates bill. One of the new specialty plates will include the Stennis Flag along with the phrase, \"History + Hope + Hospitality\". This was the first time that the Stennis flag's design received some form of state sanction by being used in an official capacity.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lee|first=China |date=April 17, 2019 |title=Mississippi residents can display state flag minus Confederate battle emblem with new specialty license plate|url=https://www.wmcactionnews5.com/2019/04/18/mississippi-residents-can-display-state-flag-minus-confederate-battle-emblem-with-new-specialty-license-plate/|work=[[WMC-TV]] |location=[[Jackson, Mississippi]] |access-date=April 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/apnewsbreak-mississippi-flag-minus-rebel-x-on-license-plate/2019/04/17/f8c0e010-612c-11e9-bf24-db4b9fb62aa2_story.html?noredirect=on|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190426173901/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/apnewsbreak-mississippi-flag-minus-rebel-x-on-license-plate/2019/04/17/f8c0e010-612c-11e9-bf24-db4b9fb62aa2_story.html?noredirect=on|url-status=dead|title=Mississippi drivers can put flag minus rebel X on license - The Washi\u2026|date=April 26, 2019|archivedate=April 26, 2019|website=archive.is}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/439378-mississippi-governor-signs-bill-permitting-license-plates-with|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190426173657/https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/439378-mississippi-governor-signs-bill-permitting-license-plates-with|url-status=dead|title=Mississippi governor signs bill permitting license plates with altern\u2026|date=April 26, 2019|archivedate=April 26, 2019|website=archive.is}}</ref>\n\n==Pledge of Allegiance==\nThe pledge to the state flag is:\n\n{{quote|I salute the flag of Mississippi and the [[U.S. state|sovereign state]] for which it stands with pride in her history and achievements and with confidence in her future under the guidance of [[Ceremonial deism|Almighty God]].|source=MS Code \u00a7 37-13-7 (2018)}}\n\nThe Mississippi Code provides: \"The pledge of allegiance to the Mississippi flag shall be taught in the public schools of this state, along with the pledge of allegiance to the United States flag.\"<ref>{{cite book |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=https://law.justia.com/codes/mississippi/2018/title-37/chapter-13/in-general/section-37-13-7/|title=MS Code \u00a7 37-13-7 (2018)}}</ref>\n\n==See also==<!-- EDITORS NOTE: This section should primarily contain lists linked to the main article which are directly related to the flag. Thank you. -->\n{{Portal|Heraldry|Mississippi}}\n* [[List of flags by design]]\n* [[List of Mississippi state symbols]]\n* [[List of U.S. state, district, and territorial insignia]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Cannon |first=Devereaux D., Jr. |date=2005 |orig-year=1st pub. St. Lukes Press:1988 |chapter=Chapter 7: State Flags |title=The Flags of the Confederacy: An Illustrated History |others=Cover design by Larry Pardue |location=[[Gretna, Louisiana|Gretna]] |publisher=[[Pelican Publishing Company]] |pages=34\u201348 |isbn=978-1-565-54109-2 |oclc=970744690}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Flags of Mississippi}}\n<!--\n  ===============================================================================\n   WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS. Only a limited number of new links\n   should be added to this article. PLEASE DO NOT ADD external links to sites with\n   information already in the article or in its sources.\n\n   See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for further details\n  ===============================================================================\n-->\n* {{FOTW|id=us-ms|title=Mississippi (U.S.)}}\n* [https://law.justia.com/codes/mississippi/2013/title-3/chapter-3/section-3-3-16/ Text] of the Mississippi Flag Code (MS Code \u00a7 3-3-16)\n<!-- EDITORS NOTE: Please follow the [[WP:EL]] guideline where possible and consider discussing on the talk page. Thank you. -->\n\n{{US state flags}}\n{{Mississippi}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Flags of Mississippi| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:1894 establishments in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Flag controversies in the United States|Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Flags introduced in 1894|Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Symbols of Mississippi|Flag]]\n[[Category:United States state flags|Mississippi]]\n", "name_user": "24.237.221.247", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(I added a citation)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flag_of_Mississippi"}
{"title_page": "P. Ayyaneth", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n[[File:P. Ayyaneth.jpg|right|200px]]\n'''Pathrose Ayyaneth''' (1928 - 2008), popularly known as '''P. Ayyaneth''', was a [[Malayalam|Malayalam-language]] novelist, short story writer and poet from [[Kerala]], [[India]]. Born in 1928 at [[Nariyapuram]], [[Pathanamthitta]], Ayyaneth graduated in mathematics and worked as a teacher, journalist and government employee. After retiring as assistant director of the Bureau of Economics and Statistics, he practised as a lawyer. His entered the literary field with a poem titled ''Parimalam'', written at the age of 15. He soon began writing prose. Many of his novels appeared as serials in periodicals in 1960s and 1970s. A prolific writer, he had penned 40 novels, 10 short story collections, a few plays and articles. His widely read novels included ''Manushya Nee Mannakunnu, Thiruseshippu'' and ''Vazhvemayam''. Six of his novels have become films. Ayyaneth died in a hospital on 17 June 2008 of injuries suffered in a road accident. He was hit by a scooter while he was crossing the road near his house in [[Kumarapuram]].<ref>[http://www.hindu.com/2008/06/18/stories/2008061855111000.htm \"Writer P. Ayyaneth passes away\"]. ''The Hindu''. 18 June 2008. Retrieved 8 July 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.dnaindia.com/india/1171791/report-noted-writer-p-ayyaneth-died \"Noted writer P Ayyaneth died\"]. ''Daily News and Analysis''. 18 June 2008. Retrieved 8 July 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.sify.com/mobile/news/malayalam-writer-ayyaneth-dead-news-national-jegrADhgced.html \"Malayalam writer Ayyaneth dead\"]. Sify.com. 18 June 2008. Retrieved 8 July 2013.</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Malayalam Literature |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ayyaneth, P.}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Pathanamthitta]]\n[[Category:Indian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Malayali people]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language writers]]\n[[Category:Malayalam novelists]]\n[[Category:Malayalam short story writers]]\n[[Category:Malayalam poets]]\n[[Category:Pedestrian road incident deaths]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in India]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian novelists]]\n[[Category:Indian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n[[File:P. Ayyaneth.jpg|right|200px]]\n'''Pathrose Ayyaneth''' (1928 - 2008), popularly known as '''P. Ayyaneth''', was a [[Malayalam|Malayalam-language]] novelist, short story writer and poet from [[Kerala]], [[India]]. Born in 1928 at [[Nariyapuram]], [[Pathanamthitta]], Ayyaneth graduated in mathematics and worked as a teacher, journalist and government employee. After retiring as assistant director of the Bureau of Economics and Statistics, he practised as a lawyer. His entered the literary field with a poem titled ''Parimalam'', written at the age of 15. He soon began writing prose. Many of his novels appeared as serials in periodicals in 1960s and 1970s. A prolific writer, he had penned 40 novels, 10 short story collections, a few plays and articles. His widely read novels included ''Manushya Nee Mannakunnu, Thiruseshippu'' and ''Vazhvemayam''. Six of his novels have become films. Ayyaneth died in a hospital on 17 June 2008 of injuries suffered in a road accident. He was hit by a scooter while he was crossing the road near his house in [[Kumarapuram]].<ref>[http://www.hindu.com/2008/06/18/stories/2008061855111000.htm \"Writer P. Ayyaneth passes away\"]. ''The Hindu''. 18 June 2008. Retrieved 8 July 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.dnaindia.com/india/1171791/report-noted-writer-p-ayyaneth-died \"Noted writer P Ayyaneth died\"]. ''Daily News and Analysis''. 18 June 2008. Retrieved 8 July 2013.</