{"title_page": "Ousmane Sonko", "text_new": "{{cleanup rewrite|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = \n| image       = \n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1974|07|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Thi\u00e8s]], [[Senegal]]\n| residence   = Senegal\n| nationality = Senegal\n| education   = Training and Research Unit of Legal Sciences at Gaston Berger University in Saint-Louis, Senegal\n| occupation  = Politician, tax inspector\n| spouse      = \n| partner     =\n| children    = 6\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     = \n| footnotes   =\n}}\n\n'''Ousmane Sonko''' was born in [[Thi\u00e8s]], [[Senegal]] in 1974. He is an author of two books. He was a chief tax inspector in Senegal, and a tax justice advocate. Sonko is the youngest candidate running for president in the 2019 election in Senegal.  The election was held on February 24, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.africa-confidential.com/profile/id/4030/Ousmane_Sonko|title=Ousmane Sonko {{!}} Who's Who Profile {{!}} Africa Confidential|website=www.africa-confidential.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-28}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/2018/05/22/west-africa-leaks-project-exposes-new-offshore-scandals/,%20https://www.taxjustice.net/2018/05/22/west-africa-leaks-project-exposes-new-offshore-scandals/|title=West Africa Leaks project exposes new offshore scandals|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref> He is one of the five candidates running in the 2019 presidential election in [[Senegal]]. He is seen as a rising star of hope for Senegal and for Africa.  He along with the other four candidates are challenging the incumbent president of Senegal [[Macky Sall]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leadership.ng/2019/02/19/senegal-meet-youngest-presidential-candidate-ousmane-sonko/|title=Senegal : Meet Youngest Presidential Candidate, Ousmane Sonko|last=Oketade|first=Oyinloluwa|date=2019-02-19|website=Leadership Newspaper|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-28}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/tag/ousmane-sonko/|title=Ousmane Sonko Archives|website=SABC News - Breaking news, special reports, world, business, sport coverage of all South African current events. Africa's news leader.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/video/2019/02/19/young-fashion-designer-picks-sonko-in-se?videoId=516825376|title=Young fashion designer picks Sonko in Senegal vote {{!}} Reuters.com|last=Reuters|first=Thomson|date=2019-02-19|website=U.S.|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.rfi.fr/africa/20190203-senegal-presidential-election-campaign-macky-sall-khalifa-karim-wade|title=Senegal kicks off presidential election campaign|date=2019-02-03|website=RFI|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-28}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/22/africa/senegal-election-sonko/index.html|title=Senegal's youngest presidential candidate wants to cut colonial-era ties with France|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nOusmane Sonko was born in Thi\u00e8s, Senegal. He spent his childhood in [[S\u00e9bikotane]] and [[Casamance]]. S\u00e9bikotane is near [[Dakar]]. All of his schooling has  been in the country of Senegal. His father is from Casamance and his mother is from Khombole.<ref>https://africandailyvoice.com/en/2019/01/24/senegal-who-ousmane-sonko-youngest-presidential-candidate/\n</ref>\n\nHe received his he baccalaureate in 1993.\n\nIn 1999 - Sonko received a master's degree from Gaston Berger University of  [[Saint-Louis, Senegal]]. He got his master's degree in the Juridical Sciences specializing in public law.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1993, he obtained a graduate degree from Gaston Berger University in Saint-Louis, Senegal. He studied and was trained in the research unit of Legal Sciences. At Gaston Berger he obtained a specialization in Public Law. After Sonko obtained his master's degree he attended National School of Administration and Judiciary (ENAM). Sonko spent 15 years of service as a tax specialist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icij.org/blog/2018/12/icijs-10-most-shared-stories-in-2018/|title=From Implant Files to West Africa Leaks, 2018's most-shared stories|date=2018-12-30|website=ICIJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref> Sonko is the president of the political party PASTEF-Les Patriotes \"[[Patriots of Senegal for Ethics, Work and Fraternity]]\". The PASTEF was created in January 2014. He is also the elected deputy of the NDAWI ASKAN WI / People\u2019s Alternative coalition in the National Assembly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pastefusa.com/president-ousmane-sonko/|title=PRESIDENT OUSMANE SONKO \u2013 PASTEF USA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Sonko was a tax inspector turned whistle blower. He exposed corrupt practices such as offshore tax havens, by the Senegalese elite. He was terminated because of his activism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/the-five-candidates-running-in-senegal-s-presidential-election/4792319.html|title=The Five Candidates Running in Senegal's Presidential Election|website=VOA|language=en|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cenozo.org/en/articles/95-west-africa-leaks-offshore-holdings-of-west-africas-officials-traffickers-revealed|title=Cenozo {{!}} West Africa Leaks: offshore holdings of West Africa\u2019s officials, traffickers revealed|website=cenozo.org|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref> He exposed corrupt practices such as the $50 million mineral sands processing plant in Senegal. SNC Lavalin-Mauritius Ltd a Canadian company used a shell so as to avod paying estimated $8.9 million in taxes. He is the author of the P\u00e9trole et gaz au S\u00e9n\u00e9gal (French Edition), published in 2017. The book chronicles and focuses on the Petro-Tim affair scandals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.africa-confidential.com/profile/id/4030/Ousmane_Sonko|title=Ousmane Sonko {{!}} Who's Who Profile {{!}} Africa Confidential|website=www.africa-confidential.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref> In 2017 Sonko was elected deputy to the National Assembly of Senegal as the voice of the NDAWI ASKAN WI/People\u2019s Alternative coalition. In 2018 he authored the book titled \"Solutions\".\n\nSonko is running for president in the 2019 election in Senegal as a tax justice candidate. He has said that; \"A tax haven can be a haven for multinationals who want to avoid paying taxes. But for the country, it's hell\". Senega still uses the French franc along with seven other Francophone countries in West Africa. Sonko wants to replace the CFA franc with a domestic curre gradually. \"Sonko proposes a gradual, prudent and responsible exit from the franc CFA monetary system that is holding our economies hostage,\" says Mamadou Yauck, a Pastef Partie activist for the Sonko campaign.\n\nIn the Senegal election for president on February 24, 2019 Mackey Sall was re-elected winning 58% of the vote.  Idrissa Seck received 21% of the vote, and Ousmane Sonko came in  third with  16%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-senegal-election-macky-sall-idUSKCN1QM254|title=Senegal's president officially declared election winner|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\n==Quotes==\n\u2018\u2018One of the first programme to addressed, if I were to be elected, is the reconstruction of the \u201cEmile Badiane Bridge\u201d. Look at the state of this bridge\u2026 We will not wait to experience a second tragedy like the one of the boat \u201cJoola\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.africanews.com/2019/02/18/meet-senegal-s-youngest-presidential-candidate-ousmane-sonko/|title=Meet Senegal's youngest presidential candidate, Ousmane Sonko|last=AfricaNews|date=2019-02-18|website=Africanews|language=en|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\nOusmane Sonko, is quoted as saying, \"many West African tax authorities are doubly plagued: They don\u2019t have the means to investigate complex foreign transactions, and, when investigators do make headway, politicians find ways to torpedo their small successes.\n\nSonko said the situation is made worse by general ignorance of the importance of corporate tax \u2013 or any tax \u2013 to society.\n\n\u201cIf you talk about \u2018tax havens\u2019 in some countries in Africa, people will look at you and think you\u2019re insane\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.africafocus.org/docs18/wa1806.php|title=West Africa/Global: Tax Evasion without Borders|website=www.africafocus.org|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\n\u201cWe have the potential, but our wealth is sold off to multinationals that are already extremely rich and whose home countries are also rich\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icij.org/blog/2018/12/icijs-10-most-shared-stories-in-2018/|title=From Implant Files to West Africa Leaks, 2018's most-shared stories|date=2018-12-30|website=ICIJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\n\u201cWhen people don\u2019t even understand what taxes are, acting on something like the [[Paradise Papers]] is challenging\u201d.<ref>\n{{Cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/2018/05/22/west-africa-leaks-project-exposes-new-offshore-scandals/,%20https://www.taxjustice.net/2018/05/22/west-africa-leaks-project-exposes-new-offshore-scandals/|title=West Africa Leaks project exposes new offshore scandals|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\nQuotes by, Ousmane Sonko\n\n==See also==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r8mdNahdo4M&t=260s Paradise Papers: The True Story Behind The Secret Nine-Month Investigation (HBO)]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sonko, Ousmane}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Senegalese politicians]]\n[[Category:Senegalese writers]]\n[[Category:Senegalese men]]\n[[Category:Senegalese diplomats]]\n[[Category:Senegalese democracy activists]]\n[[Category:People from Thi\u00e8s Region]]\n", "text_old": "{{cleanup rewrite|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = \n| image       = \n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1974|07|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Thi\u00e8s]], [[Senegal]]\n| residence   = Senegal\n| nationality = Senegal\n| education   = Training and Research Unit of Legal Sciences at Gaston Berger University in Saint-Louis, Senegal\n| occupation  = Politician, tax inspector\n| spouse      = \n| partner     =\n| children    = 6\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| signature   =\n| website     = \n| footnotes   =\n}}\n\n'''Ousmane Sonko''' was born in [[Thi\u00e8s]], [[Senegal]] in 1974. He is an author of two books. He was a chief tax inspector in Senegal, and a tax justice advocate. Sonko is the youngest candidate running for president in the 2019 election in Senegal.  The election was held on February 24, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.africa-confidential.com/profile/id/4030/Ousmane_Sonko|title=Ousmane Sonko {{!}} Who's Who Profile {{!}} Africa Confidential|website=www.africa-confidential.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-28}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/2018/05/22/west-africa-leaks-project-exposes-new-offshore-scandals/,%20https://www.taxjustice.net/2018/05/22/west-africa-leaks-project-exposes-new-offshore-scandals/|title=West Africa Leaks project exposes new offshore scandals|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref> He is one of the five candidates running in the 2019 presidential election in [[Senegal]]. He is seen as a rising star of hope for Senegal and for Africa.  He along with the other four candidates are challenging the incumbent president of Senegal [[Macky Sall]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leadership.ng/2019/02/19/senegal-meet-youngest-presidential-candidate-ousmane-sonko/|title=Senegal : Meet Youngest Presidential Candidate, Ousmane Sonko|last=Oketade|first=Oyinloluwa|date=2019-02-19|website=Leadership Newspaper|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-28}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sabcnews.com/sabcnews/tag/ousmane-sonko/|title=Ousmane Sonko Archives|website=SABC News - Breaking news, special reports, world, business, sport coverage of all South African current events. Africa's news leader.|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/video/2019/02/19/young-fashion-designer-picks-sonko-in-se?videoId=516825376|title=Young fashion designer picks Sonko in Senegal vote {{!}} Reuters.com|last=Reuters|first=Thomson|date=2019-02-19|website=U.S.|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.rfi.fr/africa/20190203-senegal-presidential-election-campaign-macky-sall-khalifa-karim-wade|title=Senegal kicks off presidential election campaign|date=2019-02-03|website=RFI|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-28}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/22/africa/senegal-election-sonko/index.html|title=Senegal's youngest presidential candidate wants to cut colonial-era ties with France|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=2019-02-23}}</ref>\n\n==Early Life==\nOusmane Sonko was born in Thi\u00e8s, Senegal. He spent his childhood in [[S\u00e9bikotane]] and [[Casamance]]. S\u00e9bikotane is near [[Dakar]]. All of his schooling has  been in the country of Senegal. His father is from Casamance and his mother is from Khombole. <ref>https://africandailyvoice.com/en/2019/01/24/senegal-who-ousmane-sonko-youngest-presidential-candidate/\n</ref>\n\nHe received his he baccalaureate in 1993.\n\nIn 1999 - Sonko received a master's degree from Gaston Berger University of  [[Saint-Louis, Senegal]]. He got his master's degree in the Juridical Sciences specializing in public law.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1993, he obtained a graduate degree from Gaston Berger University in Saint-Louis, Senegal. He studied and was trained in the research unit of Legal Sciences. At Gaston Berger he obtained a specialization in Public Law. After Sonko obtained his master's degree he attended National School of Administration and Judiciary (ENAM). Sonko spent 15 years of service as a tax specialist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icij.org/blog/2018/12/icijs-10-most-shared-stories-in-2018/|title=From Implant Files to West Africa Leaks, 2018's most-shared stories|date=2018-12-30|website=ICIJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref> Sonko is the president of the political party PASTEF-Les Patriotes \"[[Patriots of Senegal for Ethics, Work and Fraternity]]\". The PASTEF was created in January of 2014. He is also the elected deputy of the NDAWI ASKAN WI / People\u2019s Alternative coalition in the National Assembly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pastefusa.com/president-ousmane-sonko/|title=PRESIDENT OUSMANE SONKO \u2013 PASTEF USA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Sonko was a tax inspector turned whistle blower. He exposed corrupt practices such as offshore tax havens, by the Senegalese elite. He was terminated because of his activism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/the-five-candidates-running-in-senegal-s-presidential-election/4792319.html|title=The Five Candidates Running in Senegal's Presidential Election|website=VOA|language=en|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cenozo.org/en/articles/95-west-africa-leaks-offshore-holdings-of-west-africas-officials-traffickers-revealed|title=Cenozo {{!}} West Africa Leaks: offshore holdings of West Africa\u2019s officials, traffickers revealed|website=cenozo.org|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref> He exposed corrupt practices such as the $50 million mineral sands processing plant in Senegal. SNC Lavalin-Mauritius Ltd a Canadian company used a shell so as to avod paying estimated $8.9 million in taxes. He is the author of the P\u00e9trole et gaz au S\u00e9n\u00e9gal (French Edition), published in 2017. The book chronicles and focuses on the Petro-Tim affair scandals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.africa-confidential.com/profile/id/4030/Ousmane_Sonko|title=Ousmane Sonko {{!}} Who's Who Profile {{!}} Africa Confidential|website=www.africa-confidential.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref> In 2017 Sonko was elected deputy to the National Assembly of Senegal as the voice of the NDAWI ASKAN WI/People\u2019s Alternative coalition. In 2018 he authored the book titled \"Solutions\". \n\nSonko is running for president in the 2019 election in Senegal as a tax justice candidate. He has said that; \"A tax haven can be a haven for multinationals who want to avoid paying taxes. But for the country, it's hell\". Senega still uses the French franc along with seven other Francophone countries in West Africa. Sonko wants to replace the CFA franc with a domestic curre gradually. \"Sonko proposes a gradual, prudent and responsible exit from the franc CFA monetary system that is holding our economies hostage,\" says Mamadou Yauck, a Pastef Partie activist for the Sonko campaign.\n\nIn the Senegal election for president on February 24, 2019 Mackey Sall was re-elected winning 58% of the vote.  Idrissa Seck received 21% of the vote, and Ousmane Sonko came in  third with  16%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-senegal-election-macky-sall-idUSKCN1QM254|title=Senegal's president officially declared election winner|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\n==Quotes==\n\u2018\u2018One of the first programme to addressed, if I were to be elected, is the reconstruction of the \u201cEmile Badiane Bridge\u201d. Look at the state of this bridge\u2026 We will not wait to experience a second tragedy like the one of the boat \u201cJoola\". <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.africanews.com/2019/02/18/meet-senegal-s-youngest-presidential-candidate-ousmane-sonko/|title=Meet Senegal's youngest presidential candidate, Ousmane Sonko|last=AfricaNews|date=2019-02-18|website=Africanews|language=en|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\nOusmane Sonko, is quoted as saying, \"many West African tax authorities are doubly plagued: They don\u2019t have the means to investigate complex foreign transactions, and, when investigators do make headway, politicians find ways to torpedo their small successes.\n\nSonko said the situation is made worse by general ignorance of the importance of corporate tax \u2013 or any tax \u2013 to society.\n\n\u201cIf you talk about \u2018tax havens\u2019 in some countries in Africa, people will look at you and think you\u2019re insane\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.africafocus.org/docs18/wa1806.php|title=West Africa/Global: Tax Evasion without Borders|website=www.africafocus.org|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\n\u201cWe have the potential, but our wealth is sold off to multinationals that are already extremely rich and whose home countries are also rich\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icij.org/blog/2018/12/icijs-10-most-shared-stories-in-2018/|title=From Implant Files to West Africa Leaks, 2018's most-shared stories|date=2018-12-30|website=ICIJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\n\u201cWhen people don\u2019t even understand what taxes are, acting on something like the [[Paradise Papers]] is challenging\u201d.<ref>\n{{Cite web|url=https://www.taxjustice.net/2018/05/22/west-africa-leaks-project-exposes-new-offshore-scandals/,%20https://www.taxjustice.net/2018/05/22/west-africa-leaks-project-exposes-new-offshore-scandals/|title=West Africa Leaks project exposes new offshore scandals|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref>\n\nQuotes by, Ousmane Sonko\n\n==See also==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r8mdNahdo4M&t=260s Paradise Papers: The True Story Behind The Secret Nine-Month Investigation (HBO)]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sonko, Ousmane}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Senegalese politicians]]\n[[Category:Senegalese writers]]\n[[Category:Senegalese men]]\n[[Category:Senegalese diplomats]]\n[[Category:Senegalese democracy activists]]\n[[Category:People from Thi\u00e8s Region]]\n", "name_u