{"title_page": "Ottwell Binns", "text_new": "{{short description|British novelist and minister}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{orphan|date=April 2015}}\n{{unreferenced|date=April 2015}}\n}}\n\n'''Ottwell Binns''' (1872 - 1935) was a British [[novelist]] and [[General Assembly of Unitarian and Free Christian Churches|Unitarian]] minister.  Binns was a prolific author, publishing many novels of adventure and mystery, from 1917 to 1939. His publisher in Britain was [[Ward Lock]]. Though he died in 1935, Ward Lock continued to publish novels under his name until 1939.  His novel ''A Mating in the Wild'' was published in the U.S. in 1920 by Alfred A. Knopf and the [[A. L. Burt]] Company.\n\nBinns also published novels with Ward Lock under the [[pseudonym]] of '''Ben Bolt'''; these were similar in subject matter and treatment to the novels published under his own name.  His stories were set in many locations, including [[Great Britain|Britain]] and the [[Continental Europe|European continent]], [[Africa]], [[Asia]], the [[Oceania|South Pacific]], the [[Caribbean]] and [[Canada]], particularly the [[Yukon]].  His novels always feature a courageous, resourceful hero and a love interest, and there is an emphasis on action and narrow escapes from danger.\n\n== Work ==\n\nA partial list of his published books includes:\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n\n* 1917  ''The Man from Maloba''\n* 1918  ''A Sin of Silence''\n* 1919  ''The Lady of the Miniature''\n* 1920  ''The Mystery of the Heart''\n* 1920  ''A Mating in the Wilds''\n* 1922  ''The Treasure of Christophe''\n* 1922  ''The Lady of North Star''\n* 1923  ''The Lifting of the Shadow''\n* 1924  ''Clancy of the Mounted Police''\n* 1925  ''The Trail of Adventure''\n* 1925  ''Java Jack''\n* 1926  ''A Gipsy of the North''\n* 1926  ''Flotsam of the Line''\n* 1928  ''Behind the Ranges''\n* 1930  ''Dan Yeo''\n* 1930  ''The Vanished Guest''\n* 1930  ''The White Hands of Justice''\n* 1931  ''The Secret Pearls''\n* 1931  ''The Grey Rat''\n* 1931  ''The Flaming Crescent''\n* 1932  ''Trader Random''\n* 1933  ''Secret Adventure''\n* 1934  ''Gold is King''\n* 1934  ''The Red Token''\n* 1935  ''The Last Door''\n* 1936  ''The Far Pursuit''\n* 1936  ''Weeds of Hate''\n* 1937  ''A Soldier of the Legion''\n* 1937  ''The Poisoned Pen''\n* 1938  ''By Papuan Waters''\n* 1938  ''A Shot in the Woods''\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n\nA partial list of novels written as Ben Bolt:\n* 1921  ''Diana of the Islands''\n* 1921  ''The Diamond Buckled Shoe''\n* 1928  ''The Jewels of Sin''\n* 1930  ''The Badge''\n* 1930  ''The Other Three''\n* 1930  ''The Coil of Mystery''\n* 1931  ''The Forest Ranger''\n* 1931  ''The Sealed Envelope''\n* 1932  ''The Subway Mystery''\n* 1933  ''The Green Arrow''\n* 1935  ''The Crooked Sign''\n* 1936  ''The Five Red Stars''\n* 1936  ''The Empty House Mystery''\n* 1937  ''By Breathless Ways''\n* 1939  ''The Girl in the Train''\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gutenberg author|id=9697}}\n* {{FadedPage|id=Binns, Ottwell|name=Ottwell Binns|author=yes}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=12641}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Binns, Otwell}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1935 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:Crime novelists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British novelist and minister}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{orphan|date=April 2015}}\n{{unreferenced|date=April 2015}}\n}}\n\n'''Ottwell Binns''' (1872 - 1935) was a British [[novelist]] and [[General Assembly of Unitarian and Free Christian Churches|Unitarian]] minister.  Binns was a prolific author, publishing many novels of adventure and mystery, from 1917 to 1939. His publisher in Britain was [[Ward Lock]]. Though he died in 1935, Ward Lock continued to publish novels under his name until 1939.  His novel ''A Mating in the Wild'' was published in the U.S. in 1920 by Alfred A. Knopf and the [[A. L. Burt]] Company.\n\nBinns also published novels with Ward Lock under the [[pseudonym]] of '''Ben Bolt'''; these were similar in subject matter and treatment to the novels published under his own name.  His stories were set in many locations, including [[Great Britain|Britain]] and the [[Continental Europe|European continent]], [[Africa]], [[Asia]], the [[Oceania|South Pacific]], the [[Caribbean]] and [[Canada]], particularly the [[Yukon]].  His novels always feature a courageous, resourceful hero and a love interest, and there is an emphasis on action and narrow escapes from danger.\n\n== Work ==\n\nA partial list of his published books includes:\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n\n* 1917  ''The Man from Maloba''\n* 1918  ''A Sin of Silence''\n* 1919  ''The Lady of the Miniature''\n* 1920  ''The Mystery of the Heart''\n* 1920  ''A Mating in the Wilds''\n* 1922  ''The Treasure of Christophe''\n* 1922  ''The Lady of North Star''\n* 1923  ''The Lifting of the Shadow''\n* 1924  ''Clancy of the Mounted Police''\n* 1925  ''The Trail of Adventure''\n* 1925  ''Java Jack''\n* 1926  ''A Gipsy of the North''\n* 1926  ''Flotsam of the Line''\n* 1928  ''Behind the Ranges''\n* 1930  ''Dan Yeo''\n* 1930  ''The Vanished Guest''\n* 1930  ''The White Hands of Justice''\n* 1931  ''The Secret Pearls''\n* 1931  ''The Grey Rat''\n* 1931  ''The Flaming Crescent''\n* 1932  ''Trader Random''\n* 1933  ''Secret Adventure''\n* 1934  ''Gold is King''\n* 1934  ''The Red Token''\n* 1935  ''The Last Door''\n* 1936  ''The Far Pursuit''\n* 1936  ''Weeds of Hate''\n* 1937  ''A Soldier of the Legion''\n* 1937  ''The Poisoned Pen''\n* 1938  ''By Papuan Waters''\n* 1938  ''A Shot in the Woods''\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n\nA partial list of novels written as Ben Bolt:\n* 1921  ''Diana of the Islands''\n* 1921  ''The Diamond Buckled Shoe''\n* 1928  ''The Jewels of Sin''\n* 1930  ''The Badge''\n* 1930  ''The Other Three''\n* 1930  ''The Coil of Mystery''\n* 1931  ''The Forest Ranger''\n* 1931  ''The Sealed Envelope''\n* 1932  ''The Subway Mystery''\n* 1933  ''The Green Arrow''\n* 1935  ''The Crooked Sign''\n* 1936  ''The Five Red Stars''\n* 1936  ''The Empty House Mystery''\n* 1937  ''By Breathless Ways''\n* 1939  ''The Girl in the Train''\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gutenberg author|id=9697}}\n* {{FadedPage|id=Binns, Ottwell|name=Ottwell Binns|author=yes}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=12641}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Binns, Otwell}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1935 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century British novelists]]\n[[Category:Crime novelists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ottwell_Binns"}
{"title_page": "List of satirical news websites", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{for|fake news|List of fake news websites}}\n{{dynamic list}}\nThis is a '''list of satirical news websites''' which have a satirical bent, are parodies of news, which consist of fake news stories for mainly humorous purposes. \n\n==Definition==\nThe best-known example is ''[[The Onion]]'', which was started in 1996.<ref>{{cite news |author=Geoff Keighley Business 2.0 |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2003/TECH/ptech/08/28/bus2.feat.onion.site/index.html |title=CNN.com - The Onion: Funny site is no joke - August 29, 2003 |publisher=Edition.cnn.com |date=2003-08-28 |accessdate=2015-11-22}}</ref>  These sites are not to be confused with [[Fake news website|fake news websites]], which deliberately publish hoaxes in an attempt to profit from gullible readers.<ref>{{cite news |author=Abby Ohlheiser |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-intersect/wp/2016/11/18/this-is-how-the-internets-fake-news-writers-make-money/ |title=This is how Facebook's fake-news writers make money |publisher=The Washington Post |date=2016-11-18 |accessdate=2018-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Joshua Gillin |url=https://www.politifact.com/punditfact/article/2017/oct/04/more-outrageous-better-how-clickbait-ads-make-mone/ |title=The more outrageous, the better: How clickbait ads make money for fake news sites |publisher=Politifact |date=2017-10-04 |accessdate=2018-08-08}}</ref>   [[News satire]] is a type of [[parody]] presented in a format typical of mainstream [[journalism]], and called a [[satire]] because of its content. News satire is not to be confused with [[fake news]] that has the intent to mislead. News satire is popular on the [[World Wide Web|web]], where it is relatively easy to mimic a credible news source and stories may achieve wide distribution from nearly any site. News satire relies heavily on [[irony]] and [[Deadpan|deadpan humor]].\n\n==List==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" <!-- Instructions: 1) Please insert new entries in [[Alphabetical order]] by \"Name\" field. 2) Entry must link to its Wikipedia article. 3) See \"Wikipedia:Write the article first\" -->\n|+List of satirical news websites\n|-\n! Name\n! Country\n! Founded\n|-\n| ''[[Awaze tribune|Awaze Tribune]]''\n| [[Eritrea]]\n| 2016\n|-\n| ''[[The Babylon Bee]]''\n| [[United States]]\n| 2016\n|-\n| ''[[Bbspot]]''\n| United States\n| 2000\n|-\n| ''[[The Beaverton]]''\n| [[Canada]]\n| 2010\n|-\n| ''[[The Betoota Advocate]]''\n| [[Australia]]\n| 2014\n|-\n| ''[[Borowitz Report]]''\n| United States\n| 2001\n|-\n| ''[[The Burrard Street Journal]]''\n| Canada\n| 2015\n|-\n| ''[[The Chaser]]''\n| Australia\n| 1999\n|-\n| ''[[El Chig\u00fcire Bipolar]]''\n| [[Venezuela]]\n| 2008\n|-\n| ''[[The Civilian]]''\n| [[New Zealand]]\n| 2013\n|-\n| ''[[ClickHole]]''\n| United States\n| 2014\n|-\n| ''[[Cracked.com|Cracked]]''\n| United States\n| 2007\n|-\n| ''[[Christwire]]''\n| United States\n| 2008\n|-\n| ''[[The Daily Bonnet]]''\n| Canada\n| 2016\n|-\n| ''[[The Daily Mash]]''\n| [[United Kingdom]]\n| 2007\n|-\n| ''[[The Daily Squib]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| 2007\n|-\n| ''[[The Daily WTF]]''\n| United States\n| 2004\n|-\n| ''[[De Speld]]''\n| [[Netherlands]]\n| 2007\n|-\n| ''[[Der Postillon]]''\n| [[Germany]]\n| 2008\n|-\n| ''[[Duffel Blog]]''\n| United States\n| 2012\n|-\n| ''[[El Koshary Today]]''\n| [[Egypt]]\n| 2008\n|-\n| ''[[El Mundo Today]]''\n| [[Spain]]\n| 2009\n|-\n| ''[[Faking News]]''\n| [[India]]\n| 2008\n|-\n| ''[[Fognews]]''\n| [[Russia]]\n| 2012\n|-\n| ''[[The Framley Examiner]]''\n| [[United Kingdom]]\n| 2001\n|-\n| ''[[Free Wood Post]]''\n| United States\n| 2011\n|-\n| ''[[The Hard Times]]''\n| United States\n| 2014\n|-\n| ''[[Huzlers]]''\n| United States\n| 2014\n|-\n| ''[[Islamica|Islamica News]]''\n| United States\n| 1999\n|-\n| ''[[:fr:Le Journal de Mourr\u00e9al|Le Journal de Mourr\u00e9al]]''\n| [[Canada]] (Qu\u00e9bec)\n| 2012\n|-\n| ''[[Khabaristan Times]]'